Patient received first dose of Pfizer covid-19 vaccine on 4/9/2021 at 1800 with her mother in attendance after consent was acquired. At 1805 patient began to feel hot and nauseous. The patient thought she was going to vomit, so she left her chair in the waiting area to head to the restroom at the back of the store. at 1807, Upon rising the patient became weak in the knees and began to collapse. The patient's mother initially supported the patient and I was called to assist the patient to the floor. The patient was very pale in appearance as she was assisted gently to the floor, avoiding any injury. EMS was called shortly after the event around 1810. The patient remained conscious however was a bit disoriented initially while lying on the floor. The patient recovered quickly, however remained nauseous and complained of feeling hot. Upon questioning the patient, she had not eaten since lunch at school at 1300. The patient was given a cold water and a sprite, of which she had a couple of drinks out of each. The patient was relocated back into a chair at 1815 as she was feeling much better. EMS arrived at 1821. EMS performed a general assessment and a blood pressure check resulting in 130/80. The patient's mother dismissed any further treatment from EMS. EMS exited the building at 1827. The patient and mother waited in the store for a while longer. Both patient and mother exited on their own, denying escort from associates at 1840.

16 2021-05-12 arthritis Patient chronic conditions (JIA, UC) previously controlled on adalimumab. Within several days of re... Read more

Patient chronic conditions (JIA, UC) previously controlled on adalimumab. Within several days of receiving COVID-19 vaccine dose #2, patient began experiencing worsening/flare of ulcerative colitis symptoms including stomach pain, diarrhea, fatigue, arthritis pain that lasted beyond the reasonable and known duration of vaccine related side-effects. Symptoms treated with dicyclomine and acetaminophen with no relief. Symptoms continued x 2 weeks. Patient ultimately required addition of budesonide to treatment regimen for ulcerative colitis and is currently having relief of symptoms.
16 2021-05-12 limb discomfort The patient felt tired and describes her eyes going dark, then passed out a few minutes after vaccin... Read more
Close
The patient felt tired and describes her eyes going dark, then passed out a few minutes after vaccination. She was vaccinated and then left the immunization room to sit down for a 15 minute waiting period. When she went to sit down, she collapsed on the floor. Her mother assisted her into a chair. She continued to be incoherent and have her eyes rolling back into her head for a few minutes. We used a cool cloth on her forehead and the back of her neck. The parents requested that we call 911. EMS arrived shortly and evaluated her. Heart rate, blood pressure, pulse ox, blood sugar and chest sounds were all within normal range. The patient stated that her arm felt heavy and "funny". She then stated that her tongue felt funny. EMS evaluated her tongue and said it looked normal. To err on the side of caution, she was taken to the hospital to determine whether or not she was having a delayed onset anaphylactic reaction. This patient has no history of seizures.
16 2021-05-13 muscle pain 12 hours post vaccine she had severe myalgia, rash on both arms and legs, headache, nausea, stomach ... Read more
Close
12 hours post vaccine she had severe myalgia, rash on both arms and legs, headache, nausea, stomach pain, and mild swelling in legs. Over the next 48 hours the rash darkened and spread to the entire body causing pain in her skin. The myalgia became nearly unbearable and both Ibuprofen and Acetaminophen didn't put a dent in the pain. One side of her face swelled so that one eye could only partially open. The nausea and stomach pain worsened so that she couldn't eat. Headache became intense. By 48 hours post vaccine she became delirious - her speech was slurred and difficult to comprehend. She would fall asleep for a few minutes and wake up unaware of where she was or what was happening. She never got a fever but did have chills. Around this time I called a relative who is a doctor to seek advice and Diphenhydramine was recommended. Benedryl helped immensely. 30 minutes after taking it she could speak clearly, was more alert, pain became tolerable, and her appetite returned. Symptoms and swelling returned when the Benedryl wore off so she continued taking it every 4 hours for the next two days until it wasn't necessary any more. The myalgia, stomach pain and headache persisted for 7 days. At 8 days post vaccine (today) a mild headache, mild and intermittent stomach pain, and mild fatigue are her only remaining symptoms. Her pediatrician cannot see her until next week but we have an appt for the 22nd.

Vaccine administered at outside facility. Patient is a 16 yo girl, admitted on 4/19 with myocarditis, s/p IVIG (4/19) after presenting with progressive new onset chest pain. She was in usual state of health up until 2 days ago when she started developing body aches, and chest pain. Patient received her 2nd Pfizer COVID vaccine last week (4/15). No known history of COVID infection. Parents brought her to the ED yesterday after she complained of dizziness, SOB, chest pain, and had a near syncopal event. EKG showed non-specific ST abnormalities with labs showing elevated troponin, mildly elevated CRP, normal CXR, negative COVID PCR. Denies fever, GI symptoms, GU symptoms, headache, rash. Once transferred to our PICU, she was worked up for myocarditis vs MIS-C. Troponin has been trended q6 and is trending up (now 11). Of note, there have been no fevers. Patient is a 16 yo girl, s/p admission (4/19-4/23/21) with myocarditis, s/p IVIG (4/19), has now been readmitted on 5/10 with myocarditis after presenting with headache and neck pain for 2 days. Following discharge from the PICU on 4/23, patient states that symptoms have lingered (low grade fevers, feeling tired, on and off chest pain). After developing a progressive headache and neck pain, she came back to the ER for re-evaluation. Upon readmission, her troponin was elevated (2.06 on 5/10). Her CBC and CMP were reassuring. Blood culture collected on 5/11 and urine culture collected on 5/10. ID consulted for workup.

delerium; Severe myalgia; full body rash; swollen legs; facial swelling; slurred speech; stomach pain and cramping; nausea; headache; injection for vaccine received same date; injection for vaccine received same date; injection for vaccine received same date; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer (patient). A 16-year-old female patient received BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE), first dose via an unspecified route of administration, administered in left arm on 15Apr2021 (Lot Number: EP7533, at the age of 16-year-old) as single dose, and second dose via an unspecified route of administration, administered in right arm on 15Apr2021 (Lot Number: EW0171, at the age of 16-year-old) as single dose for covid-19 immunization. Medical history included post streptococcal reactive arthritis and bee sting allergy. The patient's concomitant medications were not reported. On 16Apr2021, the patient experienced severe myalgia, full body rash, swollen legs, facial swelling, slurred speech, delerium, stomach pain and cramping, nausea, headache. Headache and stomach pain have lasted 7 days. Rash and myalgia lasted 5 days. Delerium, facial swelling, leg swelling and slurred speech lasted 12-24 hours and were relieved by Benedryl. The treatment for the event included Ibuprofen, Acetaminophen, diphenhydramine. The injection for vaccine received same date on 15Apr2021. Prior to vaccination, the patient was not diagnosed with COVID-19. Since the vaccination, the patient had not been tested for COVID-19. The patient did not receive any other vaccines within 4 weeks prior to the COVID vaccine. The patient did not receive any other medications within 2 weeks of vaccination. The patient was not pregnant. The outcome of the events severe myalgia and full body rash was recovered on 21Apr2021, for events stomach pain and cramping and headache was recovered on 23Apr2021, for other events delirium, swollen legs, facial swelling, slurred speech, nausea was recovering.

I got worried and went to the ED. I was assessed, diagnosed with facial paresthesia. I was offered an MRI, I declined as I did not feel that I needed it at the time. Provider prescribed 40 mg of prednisone daily for 5 days, valacyclovir 1000mg 3 times a day for 7 days. After starting prednisone facial muscle tightness I was feeling improved, still felt slight numbness more so in the mornings the next 2 days. I took the full course of prednisone, I am no longer feeling the facial symptoms. I stopped taking valacyclovir on day 3, since I felt that the prednisone was what is helping and it was harder to evenly take it 3 times a day.

I received my first shot on April 6th, 2021, and on April 18th, 2021 I experienced extreme numbness with slight pain in the fold and shoulder of my arm. I went to the ER and they took a cat scan of my neck and reported back that everything looked normal - the nurse said it was most likely Cervical Radiculopathy. Then the following morning around 11 AM, I experienced very intense burning in my chest starting on the right side, eventually moving to the left encompassing my entire upper chest. I also experienced a very bad migraine, which I am typically used to but this one was more of a pressure headache between my temples that I felt in my ears and jaw. I made the decision to go back to the ER and to a different one this time. The ER failed to administer a Covid-19 test and to take bloodwork - both faults that family and friends in the medical field have pointed out to me. The doctor there had me receive an IV, a chest X-Ray, and an EKG. The X-Ray and EKG were both normal. The doctor had ordered a Covid-19 test but the nurse forgot to administer it before my discharge. In my IV I received Benadryl and Reglan along with typical IV fluids. I was also given Pepcid and Mylanta. At the end of my visit, the doctor concluded that he thought it was my acid reflux acting up - gastroenteritis. I went home and continued to experience chest burning, tightness, occasional numbness/pains in my body, and very, very bad headaches. On top of that, I could barely swallow - it felt as if my throat was closing. I took Pepcid and Tums and neither really did anything. After seeing a Cardiologist this same week, they ordered an Echocardiogram and routine bloodwork (metabolic panel). I will also be following up with a GI, and I received a Covid-19 test today and am awaiting the results. It is possible I contracted Covid before my shot, but it is also possible that I am having a delayed reaction to my first vaccination as well. Who knows.
